            </section>
            <section>
                <h6><b>Raw vs. logarithmic scaling</b> </h5>
                <p>Some climate elements are scaled logarithmically in the scatterplot for this tool, and we provide the option to turn log-transformation off. Why log-transform? Log-transformation provides relative scaling: the logarithmic difference between 50 and 100 is the same as between 100 and 200. Many climate variables are most meaningful in a relative sense. Is a change from 1000mm to 1100mm of precipitation as significant as an change from 100mm to 200mm? In most ecological and engineering contexts, this equal 100mm increase is much more significant when it represents a 100% increase rather than a 10% increase. With the exception of temperatures, most climate elements (e.g. precipitation, heat sums, drought indices) start at zero and span many orders of magnitude. Comparisons between locations, and through time, make more sense when these variables are log-transformed.</p>
            </section>
            <section>
                <h5><b>How reliable are the climate normals?</b> </h5>
                <p>The PRISM climate surfaces are assembled by and for British Columbians, with a lot of expert review and attention to local detail. For this reason, the climate normals for the primary elements (Tmin, Tmax, and PPT) can be considered the best possible estimate for the representative locations of each BEC unit. Here are the caveats:</p>
                <ul class="browser-default">
                    <li>The representative location for a BEC unit may not be perfectly representative of a specific location that you are interested in elsewhere in that BEC unit. Our tool is designed for fairly broad-scale comparisons between BEC units. If you want climate normals for a precise location, ClimateBC is the tool for you.</li>
                    <li>Climate normals for derived elements are subject to errors associated with building the statistical relationships between daily and monthly values and extrapolating these relationships across the landscape and through time. On average, these estimates are reliable for areas with good weather station coverage, but they may be substantially biased for a particular location you are interested in. In particular, high-elevation and northern regions are poorly sampled by the network of weather stations used to statistically estimate the derived climate elements.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
            <section>
                <h5><b>How reliable are the historical time series?</b> </h5>
                <p>The CRU historical time series grid is a global product produced in England with no particular attention to the peculiarities of BC's climates and station record. The CRU data set utilizes only a tiny subset of the weather station network in British Columbia, with essentially no station representation at middle and high elevations. It uses an automated homogenization routine to adjust the time series for what appear to be inconsistencies between stations, particularly prior to 1950. These factors put substantial limits on what the time series data in this tool can reliably be used for.</p>
                <p>The historical time series are useful for:</p>
                <ul class="browser-default">
                    <li>qualitative assessment of climate change trends, particularly after 1950, at low elevations, and in the southern half of the province;</li>
                    <li>assessing year-to-year variations at a regional scale (e.g., 1998 was a warm year, 1999 was a cool year);</li>
                    <li>assessing the scale of climate change or differences between BEC units relative to the range of interannual climatic variability (e.g., the mean temperature difference between the ESSFwk1 and SBSwk1 is much less than interannual variability in winter, but greater in summer); and </li>
                    <li>assessing differences in climate variability and change at a regional scale (e.g., the interior has warmed more than the coast over the past 60 years).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>The historical time series are not reliable for:</p>
                <ul class="browser-default">
                    <li>comparing climate variability and change along elevational transects; and </li>
                    <li>precise calculation of climate change trends, particularly prior to 1950 and at mid-to-high elevations.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>To get a sense of the source data for the CRU time series, check out their <a href="https://crudata.uea.ac.uk/cru/data/hrg/cru_ts_3.23/ge/">Google Earth interface</a>. If you want reliable time series data for a particular location, your best bet is to get the data for one or more local weather stations <a href="https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/cdo-web/datatools/findstation">here</a>, <a href="https://www.pacificclimate.org/data/bc-station-data">here</a>, or <a href="http://www.ec.gc.ca/dccha-ahccd/">here</a>.</p>
            </section>
            <section>
                <h4><b>Climate Change Projections</b> </h4>
                <p>A core objective of this tool is to help people to understand what climate change means to their local environment. We provide downscaled climate change projections for two 21st-century emissions scenarios from an ensemble of six global climate models. In this tool, downscaling means calibrating the coarse-scale global climate model projections to the local climate. See <a href="http://www.pacificclimatefutures.net/en/help/climate-projections/introduction-climate-change-projections/">here</a> for an introduction to global climate models and downscaling</p>
            </section>
            <section>
                <h5><b>Ensemble of global climate models</b> </h4>
                <p>ClimateBC provides downscaled time series for individual model runs of 6 global climate models (see table below). In this beta version, our graphs show only the average of these six models. In future versions, we aim to show the individual model time series so that users can see the interannual and inter-model variability in the ensemble. We also aim to show the historical component of the global climate model projections for comparison to the observed historical climate, though historical projections are not currently available in ClimateBC. </p>
