            <section>
                <h5><b>How reliable are the projected future time series?</b> </h5>
                <p>Like the historical time series, the projected future time series are useful for some purposes, and highly unreliable for others. Global climate model ensembles have proved to be very reliable at modeling historical evolution of the global climate, but exhibit biases at regional and local scales. There are substantial differences between projections of different models for the same emissions scenarios, due to differences in the model themselves but also due to differences in the timing of climatic variability within each model run. The simple downscaling method used in ClimateBC can exaggerate these differences. Keep in mind that climate model projections start in the 19th century and are run forward without calibration to the observed climate. As a result, the transition from the observed historical climate to the modeled future climate may not be smooth, and the projected values for years in the immediate future should not be considered predictions. For all these reasons, an ensemble mean is much more reliable than individual downscaled model runs for the purpose of assessing the general trajectory of climate change.  </p>
                <p>The ensemble mean projections are useful for:</p>
                <ul class="browser-default">
                    <li>comparing differences between emmissions scenarios (RCP4.5 vs. RCP8.5);</li>
                    <li>comparing the scale of climate change in different regions (e.g. coast vs. interior);</li>
                    <li>comparing future climate conditions in one location to the historical climate of other locations (e.g. the end-of-21st-century winter temperature of the high-elevation coastal CWHvm2n is projected under RCP8.5 to be similar to the end-of-20th century climate of nearby sea level units (e.g. CWHvh2)); and</li>
                    <li>identifying novel climates (trajectories outside the current range of climates found in British Columbia).</li>
                  </ul>
                <p>The ensemble mean projections are not reliable for:</p>
                <ul class="browser-default">
                    <li>assessing changes in interannual variability (because averaging across several time series dampens variability); and </li>
                    <li>predicting conditions for individual years in the future.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
